      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Mechanical tension and metabolic stress are the two main drivers for hypertrophy, and they work together to make your muscles grow. Mechanical tension is the physical force you put on the muscle, which is the primary driver, and it's often achieved by lifting heavy loads. Metabolic stress, on the other hand, is the buildup of metabolites like lactate within the muscle during intense, high-volume work. Think of it like the pressure cooker effect—the muscle gets pumped full of metabolic byproducts from the intense work, which also contributes to growth.",
